<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06220307 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06220307 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  ADULT; MINORITY; EDUCATION; SUPPORT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Gilda Montesino's brown face crinkles with a smile as she listens to some ofthe anecdotes her student tells as he flips through his lesson manuals.;    Tomany, Gilda Montesino is more than a tutor with the Alameda County LibraryAdult Literacy Program. She's a role model.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  The Weekly  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MINORITY TUTORS SOUGHT FOR ADULTS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Unfortunately, she's one of a very few.;    While Hispanics, blacks andAsians make up more than half of the Adult Literacy Program's studentpopulation, they comprise less than 10 percent of the tutors.;    Programcoordinators want to change that. They're focusing recruiting efforts onattracting more members of minorities.;    &quot;Of course, we welcome everyone,but particularly we would like to have more cultural diversity,&quot; said SherryDrobner, director of the Adult Literacy Program.;    &quot;Culturally, it's abenefit for the students. It provides them with a role model, a mentor.&quot;;   The literacy program -- which has a waiting list of 50 people -- serves 200students in Union City, Fremont, Newark, San Lorenzo, Pleasanton, Dublin,Castro Valley, and at Santa Rita and North County jails.;    While Montesino,a Union City software engineer, said she volunteered for the program to assistall students, she has a strong desire to help Hispanics.;    &quot;I grew up in aneighborhood where 100 percent of the kids were Hispanics. I saw a lot of themgo through school and either fail or get pushed along. Many were labeled asbilingual when they were really non-lingual,&quot; said Montesino, 31, who grew upin Huntington Park.;    &quot;Hopefully, having come from the same type ofenvironment, I can bring back something a little different since I have anunderstanding of the cultural expectations -- what people enjoy and the typesof changes they've gone through.&quot;;    Her student, Carlos Martinez, 40, ofUnion City, graduated from James Logan High School, but only mastered asecond-grade reading level.;    &quot;I knew the rules and I played the game,&quot; saidMartinez, explaining how he managed to graduate.;    He may have fooled theteachers, but Martinez still felt like he had lost.;    Three years ago, thatchanged. He saw a sign on a Union City bus advertising the Adult LiteracyProgram and called. He's been in the program ever since.;    Now, Martinez, apainter, has a new goal.;    &quot;One of my main goals is to be a tutor. I'mdetermined to go to college.;    &quot;And yes, I too would like to be a role modelfor others like me.&quot;;    On this day, however, he reads the latest adultliteracy textbook at the Union City Library, where he meets with Montesinoweekly.;    &quot;Just for today I feel a peace,&quot; he reads. &quot;Just for today I caneasily feel pleased for the things I do. Just for today I am listening tome.&quot;;    IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; For information on being a tutor, call SherryDrobner or Lynne Anderson, program assistant, at the Alameda County AdultLiteracy Program at (415) 745-1488.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  SANDRA GONZALES, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910807  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  481  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday August 7, 199100220307,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>